{{about|the general concept of a being superior to humans that is worshiped as "a god"|the concept of a supreme "God" in the context of [[monotheism]]|God|God in specific religions|Conceptions of God|other uses of the term|God (disambiguation)}}
{{Multiple issues|
{{POV|date=July 2015}}
{{original research|date=July 2015}}
{{Refimprove|date=April 2016}}
}}
A '''god''' is a male [[deity]], in contrast with a [[goddess]], a female deity. While the term "goddess" specifically refers to a female deity, the plural "gods" can be applied to deities collectively, regardless of gender. The [[Greek mythology|Greek]] and [[Roman mythology|Roman]] [[pantheon (gods)|pantheons]] were ruled by [[Zeus]] and [[Jupiter (mythology)|Jupiter]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hornblower|first1=Simon|title=[[The Oxford Classical Dictionary]]|date=2003|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford|isbn=0-19-860641-9|edition=3rd}}</ref>{{Page needed|date=April 2016}}

When [[ancient Egyptian religion]] developed closer to [[monotheism]], it was [[Amun]], a male god, who rose to the most prominent place.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Redford|first1=Donald B.|title=The Oxford Essential Guide to Egyptian Mythology|date=2003|publisher=Berkley Books|location=New York|isbn=0-425-19096-X|pages=20|edition=Berkley}}</ref>{{qn|date=July 2015}}

War gods, like the rulers of the pantheon, could often be male, such as [[Ares]]/[[Mars (mythology)|Mars]] and [[Toutatis]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Duval|first1=Paul-Marie|title=Les dieux de la Gaule|date=1993|publisher=Payot|location=Paris|isbn=2-228-88621-1}}</ref>{{Page needed|date=April 2016}}

==Examples==
{{Cleanup list|section|date=April 2016}}
*[[Anubis]], god of [[mummification]] in [[Egypt]]
*[[Dyeus]], [[sky father]] for the [[Proto-Indo-Europeans]]
*[[Dyaus Pita]], the reflex of ''Dyeus'' in the [[historical Vedic religion]]
*[[Tengri]], primary chief deity and [[sky father]] of the early [[Turkic peoples]] and the [[proto-Mongols]].
*[[Zeus]], king of the gods in [[ancient Greece]]
*[[Ra]], primary/sun god in [[Ancient Egyptian mythology]]
*[[Enki]], patron god of the Mesopotamian city of [[Eridu]]
*[[Odin]]/[[Wotan]], all father, war god, and king of the gods in [[Norse mythology|Germanic mythology]]

