[[File:IBKA Logo.svg|thumb]] The '''International League of Non-religious and Atheists''' (German: ''Internationaler Bund der Konfessionslosen und Atheisten'', '''IBKA''') is an international association founded in [[Berlin]] in 1976 as "International League of Non-religious" (IBDK). It originated from the ''MIZ magazine'' and the Bund der Konfessionslosen Berlin (Union of the non-religious in Berlin) founded in 1972, and adopted the name IBKA in 1982.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ibka.org/en/infos/ibka.html |title=About us |work=IBKA website |accessdate=14 August 2015}}</ref> It has approximately 1000 members<ref>http://www.deutschlandradiokultur.de/ketzer-ohne-kaefig.1278.de.html?dram:article_id=207014</ref> and 13 coorporative Members,<ref>http://www.ibka.org/infos/korporative</ref> as well as a Scientific Council.<ref>http://www.ibka.org/infos/beirat</ref> It is registered as an [[eingetragener Verein]] (e.V.) in [[Germany]].
Among its objectives, IBKA promotes [[rationalism]] and pursues the establishment of [[human rights]] and [[scientific freedom]], as well as the [[Separation of Church and state|separation of Church and State]]. In 2014, it was amongst several secularist organisations to campaign for the right to [[euthanasia]] in Germany.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.welt.de/politik/deutschland/article125740335/Zehn-Punkte-Papier-gegen-neues-Suizid-Strafgesetz.html |title=Zehn-Punkte-Papier gegen neues Suizid-Strafgesetz |author=Matthias Kamann |work=[[Die Welt]] |date=13 March 2014 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |language=de}}</ref>
