'''John W. de Gruchy''' (born 18 March 1939) is a [[Christian theology|Christian theologian]] known for his work [[Internal resistance to apartheid|resisting apartheid]]. He is presently [[Emeritus Professor]] at the University of Cape Town and [[Extraordinary professor|Extraordinary Professor]] at the [[University of Stellenbosch]].<ref name="conversation"/><ref name="satheo"/>

== Biography ==
A native of [[Pretoria, South Africa]], de Gruchy studied at the [[University of Cape Town]], [[Rhodes University]], [[Chicago Theological Seminary]] and the [[University of Chicago]]. He has two doctorates, one in theology and another in the social sciences, and a number of [[honorary doctorates]].<ref name="conversation">{{Cite web|url=https://theconversation.com/profiles/john-de-gruchy-234208|title=John de Gruchy|last=|first=|date=|website=The Conversation|language=en|access-date=29 October 2017}}</ref>

For many years, he was [[Robert Selby Taylor]] Professor of Christian Studies at [[University of Cape Town]]. He remains an [[Emeritus Professor]] at the University of Cape Town and holds a post as an [[Extraordinary professor|Extraordinary Professor]] at the [[University of Stellenbosch]].<ref name="satheo">{{Cite web| title = Brief Bio| author = John W. de Gruchy| work = John de Gruchy: Theologian and Woodworker| accessdate = 29 October 2017| url = https://southafricantheologian.wordpress.com/about/}}</ref> A [[feschrift]] was published in his honor in 2002.<ref name="Gruchy2002">{{cite book|editor-last1=Holness|editor-first1=Lyn|editor-last2=Wüstenberg|editor-first2=Ralf K. |title=Theology in Dialogue: The Impact of the Arts, Humanities, and Science on Contemporary Religious Thought : Essays in Honor of John W. de Gruchy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qelRAzcJMlUC|year=2002|publisher=William B. Eerdmans Publishing|location=Grand Rapids, MI|isbn=978-0-86486-605-9}}</ref>

Some of his earliest works were written in the midst of [[apartheid]] in [[South Africa]], speaking out against the legislation and engaging the theology of [[Dietrich Bonhoeffer]] to argue for the liberation of the oppressed.<ref name="Gruchy1979">{{cite book|last=de Gruchy|first=John W. |title=The Church Struggle in South Africa|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=k3x0AAAAMAAJ|year=1979|publisher=William B. Eerdmans|location=Grand Rapids, MI|isbn=978-0-8028-1786-0}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=de Gruchy|first=John W. |title=Bonhoeffer and South Africa: Theology in Dialogue|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AnEcAAAAMAAJ|year=1984|publisher=W.B. Eerdmans|isbn=978-0-8028-0042-8}}</ref> After apartheid legislation was abolished in 1991, de Gruchy wrote a number of works speaking about the theological role of art in society<ref>{{cite book|last=de Gruchy|first=John W. |title=Christianity, Art and Transformation: Theological Aesthetics in the Struggle for Justice|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ByyEaR0FVYgC|year=2001|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-77205-1}}</ref> and advocating for a [[reconciliation theology|theology of reconciliation]].<ref>{{cite book|last=de Gruchy|first=John W. |title=Reconciliation: Restoring Justice|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=auja3DDuMRAC|year=2002|publisher=Fortress Press|isbn=978-1-4514-1161-4}}</ref>

