{{Sikhism sidebar}}

'''Sikhism in [[Bangladesh]]''' dates back to 1503 but has declined after the partition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.thedailystar.net/magazine/2012/07/01/heritage.htm|title=Prayers from Punjab|last=|first=|date=|website=archive.thedailystar.net|publisher=The Daily Star|access-date=2016-12-20}}</ref> Most of the Sikhs in the country are officials of Indian High Commission or pilgrims. There were eighteen historical [[Gurdwara|Gurdwaras]] in Bangladesh but now only seven are left.

== History ==
Sikhism first emerged in Bengal when [[Guru Nanak]] visited Bangladesh in 1504 and established a number of Gurdwaras.<ref name="banglapedia" /> [[Gurdwara Nanak Shahi]] (Bengali: গুরুদুয়ারা নানকশাহী) is the principal [[Sikh]] Gurdwara (prayer hall) in [[Dhaka]], Bangladesh. It is located at the campus of the [[University of Dhaka]] and considered to be the biggest of the 7 Gurdwaras in the country. After the Partition of [[India]], the Sikh community left for India.<ref name=banglapedia>{{Cite web|url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Sikhs,_The|title=Sikhs, The - Banglapedia|website=en.banglapedia.org|access-date=2016-12-20}}</ref> After the [[Indo-Pakistani War of 1971]] and [[Bangladesh Liberation War]], Indian Sikh soldiers helped renovate the Gudwaras left in Bangladesh.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sikhiwiki.org/index.php/Gurdwaras_in_Bangladesh|title=Gurdwaras in Bangladesh - SikhiWiki, free Sikh encyclopedia.|website=www.sikhiwiki.org|access-date=2016-12-20}}</ref>

